VL  - 23
IS  - 1
SP  - 151
EP  - 166
PY  - 1987
DA  - 1987/08/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0022-1996(87)80010-7
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0022199687800107
AB  - Introducing intertemporal considerations into the open economy theory of distortions and welfare does not alter the fundamental conclusions drawn in static models. Dynamic welfare is evaluated for a small open economy which is in transition from one steady-state to another. because of a change in the distortion. We demonstrate that if the change moves the new steadystate capital stock away from the socially optimal level, trade intervention is superior to free trade. This result holds even though the new steady-state under trade intervention is Pareto inferior to that under free trade.
